fQT6LQQ3pWQHPBg0aHbN0mLwA41cJvVMZms-UiRr5D2QoJFSVOP3Jr3wvEpgDrOejpZNg ) :

The most surprising announcement of all, though, were the prices. Everythin=
g stayed the same! This was not what I, or close followers of Apple like Jo=
hn Gruber ( https://daringfireball.net/ ) , expected at all. After all, App=
le=E2=80=99s strategy the past several years seemed to be focused on wringi=
ng more revenue out of existing customers. More importantly, the last year =
has seen a big increase in inflation:

What this means is that in real terms Apple=E2=80=99s products actually got=
 cheaper. Apple did, to be sure, raise prices around the world, but this is=
 better explained by the fact the company runs on the dollar, which is the =
strongest in years; to put it another way, those foreign prices are derived=
 from the U.S. price, and that price stayed the same, which means the price=
 is lower.

This doesn=E2=80=99t make much sense for the product company Apple has alwa=
ys been thought to be, and doesn=E2=80=99t fully align with the approach I =
laid out in Apple=E2=80=99s Middle Age ( https://stratechery.com/2018/apple=
s-middle-age/?access_token=3DeyJhbGciOiJSUzI1NiIsImtpZCI6InN0cmF0ZWNoZXJ5Ln=
Bhc3Nwb3J0Lm9ubGluZSIsInR5cCI6IkpXVCJ9.eyJhdWQiOiJzdHJhdGVjaGVyeS5wYXNzcG9y=
dC5vbmxpbmUiLCJhenAiOiJIS0xjUzREd1Nod1AyWURLYmZQV00xIiwiZW50Ijp7InVyaSI6WyJ=
odHRwczovL3N0cmF0ZWNoZXJ5LmNvbS8yMDE4L2FwcGxlcy1taWRkbGUtYWdlLyJdfSwiZXhwIj=
oxNjk3MTk5MzUxLCJpYXQiOjE2OTQ2MDczNTEsImlzcyI6Imh0dHBzOi8vYXBpLnBhc3Nwb3J0L=
m9ubGluZS9vYXV0aCIsInNjb3BlIjoiZmVlZDpyZWFkIGFydGljbGU6cmVhZCBhc3NldDpyZWFk=
IGNhdGVnb3J5OnJlYWQgZW50aXRsZW1lbnRzIiwic3ViIjoiUnNldVlFOGpnSGVQcFdKZjFmQWI=
0QyIsInVzZSI6ImFjY2VzcyJ9.diQSkmTauRh0WL7g3-8b3_r7dQLBfwWkzYSXIj07LgueXj5yR=
oyoaKvqSOYsdAO9LANNI0V8wiK-IPr1db2JQWDfGZB54lmHnb_7zGXBM23QE75FR-TEBGsNmeyb=
5L-Foj6jatSnCWHwLwtt8Mj-YPMtaRInkOsy8RD8YZgStvctgURmJ7WzFN7bqwWN-O9SVU5z_km=
-IkRTR8DcmeclnHsn9emQo9zlybBE6NDJfLNPOZZGxzyFMVYBp7dJv7p6AWhqytNzbpyyJM6v-A=
9yhvg6reacbW05UpdEwX8fOGhGtnhvzspudWfpgZLxMiv_-oKwCTFxDR_O5uW_zfgABA ). It =
does, though, make all kinds of sense for a services company, which is focu=
sed first-and-foremost on increasing its install base. Indeed, this is the =
missing piece from that Update I wrote about Apple=E2=80=99s changing metri=
cs. To measure its business based on users, not products, was to measure li=
ke a services company; to lower the prices of the products that lead to ser=
vices revenue is to price like one.

The rate of inflation has gone down since then, but it hasn=E2=80=99t gone =
negative:

In other words, almost every Apple product is even cheaper than it was a ye=
ar ago, when it was already much cheaper than it was the year before that! =
Here are the real prices of iPhone=E2=80=99s over the last three years (rou=
gh calculations via this site ( https://www.usinflationcalculator.com/ ) , =
with 2020 as a baseline):

2020 2021 2022 2023 2 year old iPhone $499 $477 $441 $422 1 year old iPhone=
 $599 $572 $530 $507 New iPhone $799 $763 $707 $676 iPhone Pro $999 $954 $8=
83 $846 iPhone Pro Max $1,099 $1,050 $972 $1,015

I get that inflation is not intuitive, but these are finance-focused public=
ations, and there simply is no evidence that Apple is pursuing price-raisin=
g strategy =E2=80=94 the opposite, in fact. Notice that even the iPhone Pro=
 Max, with its now-higher base model, is still cheaper than it was two year=
s ago; nearly every other model is massively cheaper than in 2020.

I stand by my narrative from last year: for years Apple talked about being =
a services company, but it was hard to take them seriously when their prici=
ng strategy seemed focus on maximizing revenue instead of maximizing their =
user base. However, that strategy has meaningfully changed over the last fe=
w years, thanks to inflation. This doesn=E2=80=99t mean that Apple won=E2=
=80=99t raise prices in the future, of course; at some point inflation will=
 force their hand. Even when that happens, though, Apple has long shown wit=
h its actions, not just its words, that it is very much a services company.

